1. Introduction¶

In 2016, over 800 million gallons of wine were produced in the United States alone, which accounts for only about 12% of the global production. The global production is estimated to be 6.6 billion gallons of wine, or 33 billion regular sized bottles! By its nature, wine suits a large variety of occasions. Whether it is served as an aperitif, subliming a three-course meal or for socializing with friends, wine can be found around all corners. Over the past few years, wine sales have captured a market share of about 17% of total alcohol retail sales in the United States. The average wine consumption went up 25% between 2005 and 2016. Barefoot, America’s #1 table brand, generated about $ 665 millions in sales in 2018.

Our goal is to acquire a deeper understanding of the wine landscape industry in the United States. We aim to acquire a large, unprocessed dataset containing thousands of wine reviews. After a thorough cleaning, we will conduct descriptive analytics and hope to discover some interesting trends and generate some insightful visualizations. From end to end, the project will be developed using Python and the relevant libraries, mainly Numpy, Pandas and Seaborn.

We will be using a large data set containing wine reviews. The dataset contains the csv file named winemag-data-130k-v2.csv. This csv file contains 10 columns and 130,000 rows of wine reviews. To provide context, the data was first scraped during the week of June 15th, 2017 from the WineEnthusiast Network (https://www.winemag.com/?s=&drink_type=wine). The reviews were again scraped on November 22nd, 2017 in order to collect the title of each review, the taster’s name, and the taster’s Twitter account handle. The scrapped dataset is hosted on Kaggle https://www.kaggle.com/zynicide/wine-reviews

The dataset consists of ten fields. The Points field is the number of points. The WineEnthusiast review rating is on a scale of 1-100. WineEnthusiast claims that they only post reviews for wines that score equal to or more than 80 out of 100. The Title field is the title of the wine review. The Variety field is used to store the type of grapes that are used to make that specific wine. An example of a Variety data entry is Pinot Noir. The Description field is a brief description of the wine being reviewed. The taster will often describe the wine’s taste, smell, feel, look, amongst others. The next field is Country which stores the country the wine is from. The Province field is used to store the state or province the wine is from. Region 1 is the area where the wine is grown such as Napa. Region 2 is an additional field to store a more specific growing area within Region 1 entry. For example, “Rutherford” located in Napa Valley, could be entered into Region 2 field. The Region 2 field can also be left blank.

The Winery field is used to store the name of the winery that made that specific wine. The Designation field is the vineyard name within the winery where the grapes are from. The Price field is the cost of one standard bottle of wine. The Taster Name field is used to store the name of the person who tasted then reviewed the wine on the platform. Lastly, the Taster Twitter Handle field is used to store the taster’s twitter handle.

2. Processing tasks to prepare data for analysis:¶

After playing around with the dataset in the preliminary phase of the analysis, we realized that the dataset is far from being processed, unlike the majority of Kaggle datasets. Rather, it seems that the dataset is simply hosted on Kaggle so that it gets a better visibility for anyone interested in diving deeper in the world of wine reviews. A number of processing tasks will be necessary before running any kind of analysis.

The data is fairly dirty. Critical processing tasks such as removing duplicated values and imputting NAs (both categorical and numerical) are necessary, as well as text processing to identify the most common words used to describe wines and extract the year the grapes were harvested, an essential aspect for any wine enthusiast.

Processing Tasks Summary¶

  • Imputting NAs
    • region_2

  • Year Extraction

What we hope to find in the data:¶

We hope to find some of the most popular wines and classify them by variety. In the descriptive part of our analysis, we hope to visualize wines by country, popularity, blend and ratings. Some of the questions we may answer are:

  • What are the top producing wine countries in terms of quantity?
  • What are the countries with the highest rated wines, regardless of quantity?
  • Where are the most costly wines made?
  • Where are the cheapest wines made?
  • Word cloud of the most common words used to describe a wine
  • Distribution of points and prices by taster’s names (if applicable)?

We will also produce descriptive statistics to better understand and grasp the data, such as the range of the points given to different wines, the mean and median ratings; but also statistics about the experts who graded those wines. Finally, we will take a look at the correlation between the different variables present in the dataset.

2.2 - Identifying Missing Values¶

What are those NAs are and what could be their relative importance in our dataset?

In [11]:
def MissingValues(df):
    total = df.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending = False) 
    # Getting the sum of null values and ordering

    percent = (df.isnull().sum() / df.isnull().count() * 100 ).sort_values(ascending = False) 
    # Getting the percent and order of null
    
    df = pd.concat([total, percent], axis=1, keys=['Total', 'Percent']) 
    # Concatenating the total and percent
    
    print(df[~(df['Total'] == 0)])
    # Returning values of nulls different of 0
    
    return

From the results, it seems like the only necessary requirements for the view is to have a title, the winery, a descritpion and the score (points). Only one variety is missing which is probably part of the requirements too.

The fact that price is missing is surprising. Perhaps the wine was tasted at a tasting event where prices may not have been available.

The most commonly missing variables are the region2 with around 61% of the data missing, which suggests that region2 is not really important. Designation and the handle of the twitter test are next, followed by the taster name and the region1.

Perhaps the designation is not necessary, and as mentionned above, tasting may have happened in an environment where tasters had the luxury to remain anonymous.

2.3 - Imputing Missing Data¶

One simple method would be to drop all rows with NAs. However, this would significantly decrease the size of our dataset, which we want to avoid in order to proceed to a thorough analysis. In addition, a dataset that is either dirty with NAs or on which NAs have been brutally removed, without much tought into it, is not ideal for machine learning purposes.

In [13]:
df.dropna().shape
Out[13]:
(20493, 13)
In [14]:
67953/130000
Out[14]:
0.5227153846153846

As we can see, dropping NAs would remove more than 50% of our data! This is not an acceptable solution. Thus, I will try to imput data case by case.

Additionally, I have found this great resource: https://napavintners.com/wines/how_to_read_a_wine_label.asp detailing what is to be written on a wine label. This information will come in handy in deciding what to do with missing values. I will only mention the characteristics that are given in the dataset.

 Mandatory Characteristics:
* Brand Name (or Title)
* Wine Type
* Producer and Bottler (or Winery)

Optional Characteristics:
* Vintage (Year)
* Special designations (or Designation)

Interestingly, we do not have a specific column designated to the year the grapes have been harvested - commonly referred to as the wine's year. I will come back to this. Furthermore, I was personally shocked to see that the vintage is not only mandatory, but to learn that up to 15% of the blend can be from a vintage other than the stated vintage year.

Region_2

Second region of origin for the wine - From the article, the first region not being mandatory, the second region is clearly optional.

In [15]:
df.region_2 = df.region_2.fillna('None')

Here, the NA simply means that there are no second region. So I just replace the NA with string 'None'.

Designation

According to the article, the designation is optional. I can then replace it with 'None'.

In [16]:
df.designation.fillna('None',inplace=True)

Again, in this case, I will replace it with 'None', as this is not a numeric value on which I can imput any kind of statistic.

This following function will be used to compute outliers across the numerical variables in the dataset. I have chosen to identify points beyond 3 standard deviations as outliers.

In [59]:
def Outliers(data): 
    
    # calculating mean and std of the array
    data_mean, data_std = np.mean(data), np.std(data)

    # seting the cut line to both higher and lower values
    cut = data_std * 3

    #Calculating the higher and lower cut values
    lower, upper = data_mean - cut, data_mean + cut

    # creating an array of lower, higher and total outlier values 
    outliers_lower = [x for x in data if x < lower]
    outliers_higher = [x for x in data if x > upper]
    outliers_total = [x for x in data if x < lower or x > upper]

    # array without outlier values
    outliers_removed = [x for x in data if x > lower and x < upper]
    
    print('Outliers lower bound: %d' % lower)
    print('Outliers upped boud: %d' % upper)
    print('Identified lowest outliers: %d' % len(outliers_lower)) # printing total number of values in lower cut of outliers
    print('Identified upper outliers: %d' % len(outliers_higher)) # printing total number of values in higher cut of outliers
    print('Identified outliers: %d' % len(outliers_total)) # printing total number of values outliers of both sides
    print('Non-outlier observations: %d' % len(outliers_removed)) # printing total number of non outlier values
    print("Total percentual of Outliers: ", round((len(outliers_total) / len(outliers_removed) )*100, 4)) # Percentual of outliers in points
    
    return

Price by Country: This graph shows that France has no competition when it comes to price. They price their wines way higher than other countries. Besides a wine from the US priced at around \$2000, France owns the totality of other wines priced above \\$1500.

In the middle tier, we have Italy, Portugal, US, Spain, Germany and to a lower extent Australia. These countries consistently price their wines between \$4 and \\$1000.

Finall, the distribution of the low-tier markets such as New-Zealand, Israel, Greece, Romania, Canada, Turkey, Uruguay and Bulgaria. Those countries seem to price their wines relatively cheaply, with few, if any, wines more expensive than roughly \$250.

Points by Country: Here we see that the countries with the highest median ratings are Germany, Austria and Canada, with a median rating of approximately 90. The country with the most expensive wines, France, does not perform any better than other countries with a median rating of about 88. On the lower end of the spectrum, Romania, Chile, Spain and Greece have the worst ratings, with a median rating of about 86.

4.4. For regular consumers, how does the distribution of points/price look like by country?¶

Regular consumers are not interested in knowing how high the price of a bottle can go. Instead, what matters to them is the price in comparison to the ratings received. For example, someone travelling to a country may want to know how the wines there are rated, and whether he should expect to pay a substantial amount of money for a wine he would be able to get somewhere else cheaper, of the same quality.

I will reproduce the same visualization as before only isolating prices below \$200 this time.

In [77]:
size(15,15)

plt.subplot(2,1,1)

                  data=df.loc[(df.country.isin(country.index.values))
                              & (df.price < 200)])
g.set_title("Price by Country Of Wine Origin", fontsize=20)
g.set_xlabel("Countries ", fontsize=15)
g.set_ylabel("Price Dist(US)", fontsize=15)
g.set_xticklabels(g.get_xticklabels(),rotation=45)

plt.show()

The picture is much clearer here. We can see that all countries have quartiles in values lower than 100 - meaning that most of their wines are affordable, and that there is a large choice for the consumer. In terms of median prices though, the most expensive countries turn out to be Canada and the United State, which is surprising considering that these two countries are not known for necessarily having the best wines. On the other hand, the distribution for France and Italy shows that there is a large choice for a median price of about \$26, which is relatively cheap.

5. Understanding the wine descriptions¶

5.1. Length of the review¶

The common idea is that the fancier the description, the richer the wine, thus the better it is. Let's check if this theory holds.

In [85]:
df = df.assign(desc_len = df['description'].apply(len))

plt.figure(figsize=(14,6))
g = sns.boxplot(x='points', y='desc_len', data=df)
g.set_title('Description Length by Points', fontsize=20)
g.set_ylabel('Description Length', fontsize = 16) # Y label
g.set_xlabel('Points', fontsize = 16) # X label
plt.show()

What we see here is that as the ranking increases, so does the description length. The median description length for a wine rated at 80 is approximately 150 characters, whereas the description length for a wine ranked 100 has a median of about 400 characters.

The evolution is fairly steady until it reaches the higher ranking wines, with a big jump from rank 97 to 98, perhaps due to a lower number of wines being ranked that high.

What does the correlation look like between the description length and the points/price?

from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS

# Function to call on the word cloud on different countries

def wordcloud(data=df):
  
    stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
    stopwords.add('full')
    stopwords.add('now')
    stopwords.add('drink')

    wordcloud = WordCloud(
        background_color='white',
        stopwords=stopwords,
        max_words=1200,
        max_font_size=300, 
        width=1500, height=1000,
        random_state=24,
        ).generate(" ".join(data['description'].astype(str)))

    print(wordcloud)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12,14))
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.title("Word Cloud - DESCRIPTION" ,fontsize=25)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show();

6. Conclusion¶

Our data exploration and visualization led to some great insights. We found that most expensive wines are rarely the oldest, and that the Bordeaux province, despite its great reputation, does not hold up quite as well in terms of overall ratings compared to other wine producing provinces. We found that some countries seem to specialize in certain niche markets - Austria does not produce many wines, but the ones it produces are ranked better without necessarily being more expensive. Romania produces cheap wines who rank on the lower end in terms of ratings. France produces some of the most expensive wines in the world. We also found that red wine is the most common blend reviewed in the dataset. Finally, we learned about Roger Voss, an eminent wine expert, worth following on Twitter for his insighful and objective reviews.

From the source wesbite, here is how the wines are reviewed:

As we have infered from the beginning, the reviews happen blind, with perhaps some context about the wine. However, the price is never available to the reviewer in order not to bias him. Thus the somewhat OK correlation of 0.41.

Which raises the question - if an eminent oenologist cannot make the difference between a highly priced wine and a cheaper wine, assigning to both wine the same ratings, why is there such a difference in the prices of wines?

We assume that there must be external factors dictating the price of a bottle, perhaps it is a very limited production, or the vineyard has been destroyed by fire, or maybe the price to harvest the grapes. It is easy to imagine that a wine for which the grapes are costly to harvest, thus producing bottles in lower quantities, will have a higher price for a similar quality compared to a wine that is easier to produce.

Similarly, the packaging and the distribution strategy can influence the price of a wine, i.e. if a wine is widely distributed with a somewhat unsophisticated packaging, the price may be lower than if the same exact wine was only available at specialty stores, with a fancier packaging.
